    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.40" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">40</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">GENERAL ANSON MILLS.
                        <lb/>
                    U.S. ARMY,(RETIRED.)</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    No 2 <hi rend="caps">DUPONT CIRCLE.
                        <lb/>
                    WASHINGTON.D.C.</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have read several times your very interesting letter of March 5th hoping that I would be able to assist you in the many questions you ask, but I have, for one of my age, been very busy, and have not been very successful in getting information that I know you desire so much</p>
                
                <p>I have a copy of the Treaty at Ft. Laramie concluded April 29, 1868, which I can furnish you if you desire, but I have not a copy of the one of 1866 for which you ask.</p>
                
                <p>About the Beecher fight which the late Gen. Geo. <hi rend="caps">A.</hi> Forsyth commanded, you will find in his "The Story of the Soldier" pages 216 to 232, published by Appleton (1900), a detailed description of that battle, which I think would be the most interesting Indian engagement in all American history for you to dwell upon in your poems. Forsyth was a personal friend of mine &#8212; one of the bravest men who ever wore our uniform, however unfortunate otherwise. He married a Miss Beaumont, the daughter of Col. Beaumont of the Cavalry, a most intelligent and excellent woman, who doubtless has Forsyth's papers wherein she could give you more details than he has given in his account of the battle, or any other person, and could perhaps tell you about the Jew Schlesinger and whether he is still living. Her address is Faer-Sith, Rockport, Mass. (Mrs. Natalie <hi rend="caps">S. B.</hi> Forsyth)</p>
                
                <p>I will send you a copy of the last Proceedings of the Order of Indian Wars as soon as published.</p>
                
                <p>I have just received the copy of your "The Song of Three Friends" and appreciate it very much, and realize now the full meaning of your epic poems.</p>
                
                <p>I am sending you a copy of "My Story", privately published, thinking it may assist you also in your studies, and beg to assure you that I will, as far as I am able, assist you in your literary enterprise by giving such information as I possibly can.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Thanking you for your kindly interest in myself, I am</salute>
                    <salute>Yours very truly,</salute> 
                
                    <signed>Anson Mills</signed>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Bancroft, Nebr.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
